@model FinanceApp.Models.Expense
<div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Add Expense</h2>
    <form asp-action="Create" method="post">
        @Html.AntiForgeryToken()
        <div>
            <label asp-for="Description" class="form-label"></label>
            <input asp-for="Description" class="form-control"/>
        </div>
        <div>
            <label asp-for="Amount" class="form-label"></label>
            <input type="number" asp-for="Amount" class="form-control" step="0.01" min="0.01"/>
        </div>
        <div>
            <label asp-for="Category" class="form-label"></label>
            <input asp-for="Category" class="form-control" />
        </div>
        <div class="text-center my-3">
            <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Add Expense</button>
        </div>
        
    </form>
</div>

@*
    This Razor view is a simple Create form for an Expense model. 
    It renders a Bootstrap-styled HTML form whose inputs are bound 
    to the Expense properties via ASP.NET Core tag helpers (asp-for).
    When submitted it sends an HTTP POST to the Create action on the 
    current controller. The view includes an anti-forgery token and 
    basic Bootstrap layout classes.

Below I explain the important pieces, why they matter, and then give 
a small, production-ready improvement of the form that adds 
validation output and a few best-practices.

Line-by-line explanation
@model FinanceApp.Models.Expense


Declares the view model type for this Razor view. asp-for and 
other tag helpers will generate name and id attributes that 
match this model’s properties.

<div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Add Expense</h2>


Basic Bootstrap container and heading. text-center 
centers the heading; mb-4 gives bottom margin.

<form asp-action="Create" method="post">
    @Html.AntiForgeryToken()


asp-action="Create": the Form Tag Helper will target the 
Create action on the current controller.

method="post": the form will submit an HTTP POST.

@Html.AntiForgeryToken() emits a hidden field that holds an 
anti-forgery token so the server can validate the request 
and protect against CSRF attacks. (Keep this or ensure 
your controller action is decorated with [ValidateAntiForgeryToken].)

<div>
    <label asp-for="Description" class="form-label"></label>
    <input asp-for="Description" class="form-control"/>
</div>


label + input use asp-for="Description". The framework will:

Render the <label for="Description"> text using metadata (display name) from the model (e.g., [Display(Name = "...")]), and

Render an <input> whose name and id match the model property so model binding on POST can populate an Expense parameter.

form-control is a Bootstrap class to style the input.

<div>
    <label asp-for="Amount" class="form-label"></label>
    <input asp-for="Amount" class="form-control" step="0.01" min="0.01"/>
</div>


Binds to Amount. step="0.01" and min="0.01" are HTML attributes t
hat help browsers constrain numeric entry (useful for monetary values). 
Note: to get an HTML <input type="number"> you should 
include type="number" on the input tag or rely on editor templates.

<div>
    <label asp-for="Category" class="form-label"></label>
    <input asp-for="Category" class="form-control" />
</div>


Binds to Category. If Category is an enum or you want a select list, you 
would replace this with a <select asp-for="Category" asp-items="...">.

<div class="text-center my-3">
    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Add Expense</button>
</div>


Centered submit button styled by Bootstrap.

How this ties to the controller and model binding

On submit, ASP.NET Core model binding looks for form fields named 
like the model properties (e.g., Description, Amount, Category) 
and attempts to bind them to the action parameter (for example: 
public async Task<IActionResult> Create(Expense expense)).

The action should validate the model (e.g., if (!ModelState.IsValid) 
return View(expense);) and typically should set 
expense.UserId = currentUserId on the server-side — do not 
accept UserId from the client.

Validation and client-side feedback

This view currently does not show validation messages. To 
enable a good user experience:

Add DataAnnotations to the Expense model (e.g., [Required], [Range], [StringLength]).

Include validation message elements in the view (asp-validation-for) 
so server-side and client-side validation messages are visible.

Ensure _ValidationScriptsPartial (or the equivalent) is included in 
the layout to enable unobtrusive client-side validation 
(requires jquery + jquery-validate + jquery-validate-unobtrusive).

Accessibility and UX notes

Use class="mb-3" (Bootstrap form spacing) on each form group 
for consistent spacing.

Use <input type="number" asp-for="Amount" ... /> for numeric 
inputs so mobile keyboards and browsers show number controls.

For dates use <input type="date" asp-for="Date" /> when the model has a Date property.

Recommended improved version

This version adds validation display, uses Bootstrap form-group spacing, 
forces type="number" for Amount, and includes a validation summary.

@model FinanceApp.Models.Expense

<div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Add Expense</h2>

    <form asp-action="Create" method="post" class="needs-validation" novalidate>
        @Html.AntiForgeryToken()

        <div asp-validation-summary="All" class="text-danger mb-3"></div>

        <div class="mb-3">
            <label asp-for="Description" class="form-label"></label>
            <input asp-for="Description" class="form-control" />
            <span asp-validation-for="Description" class="text-danger"></span>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-3">
            <label asp-for="Amount" class="form-label"></label>
            <input type="number" asp-for="Amount" class="form-control" step="0.01" min="0.01" />
            <span asp-validation-for="Amount" class="text-danger"></span>
        </div>

        <div class="mb-3">
            <label asp-for="Category" class="form-label"></label>
            <input asp-for="Category" class="form-control" />
            <span asp-validation-for="Category" class="text-danger"></span>
        </div>

        <div class="text-center my-3">
            <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Add Expense</button>
        </div>
    </form>
</div>


Notes about the improved form:

asp-validation-for outputs validation messages for each field.

asp-validation-summary="All" shows model-level and field-level errors.

novalidate + needs-validation are optional if you plan to use 
Bootstrap custom validation; client-side unobtrusive validation 
works independently if you include validation scripts.

Controller-side expectations (example)

Your controller POST action should look similar to:

[HttpPost]
[ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
public async Task<IActionResult> Create(Expense expense)
{
    if (!ModelState.IsValid)
        return View(expense);

    var userId = _userManager.GetUserId(User); // or however you get current user id
    await _expensesService.Add(expense, userId);

    return RedirectToAction("Index");
}


Always call GetUserId(User) (or equivalent) on the server and 
pass that userId to the service — do not trust client-provided user identifiers.
