What each part does

@model FinanceApp.Models.Expense
Declares the view’s model type. All asp-for tag helpers reference properties on this type.

<div class="container"> … </div>
Simple Bootstrap container for layout.

<form asp-action="Create" method="post">
A form tag helper that will post to the Create action on the current 
controller. Because method="post", the form will send a POST 
request to e.g. /Expenses/Create. When using the form tag helper, 
ASP.NET Core will also emit an anti-forgery token for POST by default 
(and your action should validate it with [ValidateAntiForgeryToken]).

label + input with asp-for="..."
The asp-for tag helper binds the element to a model property:

label asp-for="Description" generates 
<label for="Description">Description</label> 
(text comes from the property name or [Display] attribute on the model).

input asp-for="Description" generates 
<input id="Description" name="Description" value="..." />.
The name and id attributes are important because the model 
binder uses them to reconstruct the Expense object on POST.

<button type="submit">Add Expense</button>
Submits the form.

How model binding works (brief)

When the browser posts the form, ASP.NET Core looks at names like 
Description, Amount, Category and tries to bind them to an action 
parameter such as public async Task<IActionResult> 
    Create(Expense expense). Types are converted (e.g., posted "12.50" -> decimal Amount).

