<input id="Description" name="Description" class="form-control" value="" />

Helpful improvements & best practices

Validation UI
Add server-side DataAnnotations on the model and show validation messages in the view:

public class Expense
{
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [Required, MinLength(3)]
    public string Description { get; set; } = "";

    [Required, Range(0.01, 100000)]
    [DataType(DataType.Currency)]
    public decimal Amount { get; set; }

    [Required]
    public string Category { get; set; } = "";
}


In the view add asp-validation-for and validation-summary:

<form asp-action="Create" method="post">
    <div asp-validation-summary="ModelOnly"></div>

    <div>
      <label asp-for="Description"></label>
      <input asp-for="Description" class="form-control" />
      <span asp-validation-for="Description" class="text-danger"></span>
    </div>
    ...
</form>


Also include the client-side validation scripts 
(jquery.validate + unobtrusive) if you want instant client-side feedback.

Amount input type
For money use a number input with step:

<input asp-for="Amount" type="number" step="0.01" class="form-control" />


(But still validate on the server. Number input improves UX.)

Category as select
If categories are known, render a <select> instead of a free text 
    input to avoid inconsistent categories.

Anti-forgery
The form tag helper emits the antiforgery token for POST forms automatically. 
In your controller POST action use [ValidateAntiForgeryToken].

Accessibility
label produced by asp-for ties to the input's id automatically—good 
for accessibility. Keep the label visible (the tag helper will
output the display text).

Minimal controller example
public class ExpensesController : Controller
{
    private readonly ApplicationDbContext _context;
    public ExpensesController(ApplicationDbContext context) => _context = context;

    public IActionResult Create() => View();

    [HttpPost]
    [ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
    public async Task<IActionResult> Create(Expense expense)
    {
        if (!ModelState.IsValid) return View(expense);
        _context.Add(expense);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
        return RedirectToAction(nameof(Index));
    }
}

